+     * GX_VTXFMT0 as the first (GXVtxFmt) argument; this one instead passes
+     * GX_VA_TEX0 (a GXAttr enumerator, value 13 -- confirmed via
+     * include/dolphin/gx/GXEnum.h's own enum order) where GX_VTXFMT0 (0)
+     * belongs. Real hardware's own GX has no vtxfmt bounds check at all (it
+     * just computes a VAT register offset from whatever value it's given),
+     * so this silently sets up the wrong-but-not-fatal vertex-attribute-
+     * format slot on real hardware -- a genuine, latent rendering bug in
+     * the original game (this is HuSpr3DDisp, the sprite "3D warp/page-
+     * flip" hook3D effect window.c's HuWinExCreateFrame registers on every
+     * window's sprite 0) that nobody ever needed to notice. Aurora's own
+     * GXSetVtxAttrFmt DOES validate (`CHECK(vtxfmt >= GX_VTXFMT0 && vtxfmt
+     * < GX_MAX_VTXFMT, ...)`) and FATALs outright -- "invalid vtxfmt 13",
+     * caught directly (Aurora/real-rendering build -- headless's null GX
+     * shim never validates anything) the first time any window (created
+     * via HuWinExCreateFrame, reachable from OpeningExec's own window
+     * frames) actually gets drawn through this hook, matching this port's
+     * own recurring "real bug that only becomes load-bearing once a code
+     * path is exercised for the first time" pattern. Fixed to the value
+     * every neighboring call site (and simple reading of intent -- this
+     * line sets up the TEX0 *attribute*, within vertex format slot 0, same
+     * as the position attribute 4 lines up) already establishes as
+     * correct; the 2nd/3rd/4th/5th arguments are unchanged (GX_VA_TEX0 is
+     * exactly right there -- it says WHICH attribute this call configures,
+     * a completely different, correct use of the same enumerator). */
+    GXSetVtxAttrFmt(GX_VTXFMT0, GX_VA_TEX0, GX_TEX_ST, GX_F32, 0);
